<h4><a name="soviet-writers"> </a>            
Soviet Philosophers and Scientists</h4>            
Writers &#8211; scientists, philosophers, teachers &#8211; in the Soviet Union were obliged to develop their ideas in terms of the official orthodox Marxist dogma. Most of these writers cannot properly be described as Marxists, but nevertheless their work has contributed in some way or another to our understanding of Marxism.<br /> <br />            
<br /><hr />            
</td></tr>            
<tr><td width="50%" class="note" valign="top">            
<span class="author"><a href="../reference/archive/michurin/index.htm" class="small-green">I. V. Michurin</a></span>            
(1855-1935) Soviet scientist who carried out groundbreaking research in genetics.  <br />            
[<a class="biog" href="../glossary/people/m/i.htm#michurin-ivan">Biography</a>]             
<br />            
<br />            
<span class="author"><a href="../archive/semashko/index.htm" class="small">N. A. Semashko</a></span>            
(1874-1949)<br />            
Architect of Soviet Health System.            
<br />            
[<a class="biog" href="../glossary/people/s/e.htm#semashko">Biography</a>]            
<br />            
<br />            
<span class="author"><a href="../archive/vygodsky/index.htm" class="small-green">Vitaly Vygodsky</a></span>            
(1928-1998)<br />            
Soviet political economist.            
<br />            
[<a class="biog" href="../glossary/people/v/y.htm#vygodsky-vitaly">Biography</a>]            
<br />            
<br />            
<span class="author"><a href="../reference/archive/spirkin/works/dialectical-materialism/index.html" class="small">Alexander Spirkin</a></span>            
