<tr><td colspan="2" class="note" valign="top">            
<img src="../glossary/people/v/pics/vygotsky.jpg" alt="Lev Vygotsky" hspace="10" vspace="12" border="1" align="right" height="100" />            
<a name="soviet-marxism"></a>            
<h4>Soviet Marxism</h4>            
Despite the suppression of Trotskyism and the impossibility of open political discussion in Stalin's Soviet Union, a few Russians continued the development of Marxism in Psychology, Medicine, Law and the Sciences. This &#8220;non-political Marxism&#8221;  only dared to show its political colours after Stalin's death. <br />            
</td></tr>            
            
            
<tr>            
<td width="50%" class="note" valign="top">            
<span class="author"><a href="pashukanis/index.htm" class="small-green">Evgeny Pashukanis</a></span>            
(1891-1937) 10+<br />            
Foremost exponent of the Marxist approach to Law.            
<br />            
[<a class="biog" href="pashukanis/biog/biogintro.htm">Biography</a>]            
