<tr><td width="50%" class="note" valign="top" colspan="2">            
<hr /> <br />            
<img src="../glossary/people/p/pics/pankhurst-emmeline.jpg" alt="Emmeline Pankhurst" hspace="10" vspace="2" border="1" align="right" height="100" />            
<img src="../glossary/people/s/pics/sand-george.jpg" alt="George Sand" hspace="10" vspace="2" border="1" align="left" height="100" />            
<h4><a href="../subject/women/feminists.htm" name="feminism">Feminists</a></h4>            
From the 18th century up to the present, women fighting against their oppression by patriarchal structures have developed political science, ethics and critical philosophy and contributed to the development of revolutionary theory. Many were Marxists.<br /> <br />            
<hr />            
</td></tr>            
            
<tr>            
<td width="50%" class="note" valign="top"><a name="1759"> </a>            
<span class="author"><a href="../reference/archive/wollstonecraft-mary/index.htm" class="small-green">Mary Wollstonecraft</a></span>            
(1759-1797)  <br />            
English radical who was the first woman to systematically enquire into the causes of women's oppression.            
<br />            
[<a class="biography" href="../glossary/people/w/o.htm#wollstonecraft-mary">Full Biography</a>]            
</td>            
            
<td width="50%" class="note" valign="top" colspan="2">            
<span class="author"><a href="../reference/archive/mill-john-stuart/1869/subjection-women/index.htm" class="small-green">Harriet Taylor</a></span>            
(1856-1915) <br />            
Friend of John Stuart Mill, and her work was published under his name, one of the earliest arguments for the emancipation of women, in the tradition of classical liberalism.            
<br />            
[<a class="biography" href="../glossary/people/t/a.htm#taylor-harriet">Full Biography</a>]            
</td></tr>            
            
            
<tr>            
